ts.  \n6. **Avoid unnecessary calls:** once a title is known and its page has been looked up, do not search for it again. Do not retrieve pages that are not directly needed to confirm the three entities.  \n7. **When calling `finish`**, leave `next_tool_args` empty (`{}`); the subsequent extraction module will read the trajectory and output the final list of titles.\n[3] **Output format (exactly as shown, one field per line):**\n[4] ```\n\nOutput (JSON only):'}], 'image_urls': []}, response={'token_ids': [4913, 291, 1199, 66582, 453, 3252, 8156, 16221, 2198, 1252, 788, 15, 1335, 1318, 3252, 22043, 264, 1565, 7859, 63, 323, 279, 1482, 1565, 83787, 7808, 8253, 1128, 1995, 374, 2058, 7402, 11, 3293, 458, 8311, 5392, 11, 323, 13837, 1181, 5977, 11, 39816, 3080, 498, 614, 20190, 279, 26587, 6816, 429, 6644, 279, 3070, 46385, 2326, 12460, 4549, 15311, 334, 4362, 311, 10146, 320, 269, 83177, 8, 279, 3717, 13, 5005, 8286, 9755, 448, 1565, 30150, 63, 1189, 36828, 453, 3252, 5090, 16221, 2198, 1318, 3252, 10227, 6248, 11, 5978, 279, 2326, 15311, 525, 12460, 11, 5961, 9760, 11, 323, 7225, 30403, 1189, 92, 13989, 151645], 'raw_content': [{'finish_reason': 'stop', 'role': 'assistant', 'content': '{"edits":[{"op":"replace_section","index":0,"text":"Given a `claim` and the current `trajectory`, determine what information is still missing, select an appropriate tool, and specify its arguments, repeating until you have gathered the Wikipedia pages that contain the **exact three distinct article titles** needed to verify (or refute) the claim. Then signal completion with `finish`."},{"op":"append_section","text":"Before finish, ensure the three titles are distinct, directly relevant, and fully retrieved."}]}'}]}, reward=None, metadata={'request': {'type': 'chat', 'model': 'Qwen/Qwen3-8B', 'max_tokens': 256, 'temperature': 0.8, 'streaming': False}, 'response': {'id': 'chatcmpl-59e22f4cb858469784d15d57d216cb4a', 'model': 'Qwen/Qwen3-8B'}, 'response_id': 'chatcmpl-59e22f4cb858469784d15d57d216cb4a', 'agent_name': '*'}), Triplet(prompt={'token_ids': [], 'raw_content': [{'role': 'user', 'content': 'Given a `claim` and the current `trajectory`, determine what information is still missing, select an appropriate tool, and specify its arguments, repeating until you have gathered the Wikipedia pages that contain the **exact three distinct article titles** needed to verify (or refute) the claim. Then signal completion with `finish`.\n\n**Instructions for the Predict module (`claim, trajectory -> next_thought, next_tool_name, next_tool_args`):**\n\n1. **Read the claim carefully.** Identify the three entities (people, places, works, concepts, etc.) that are *explicitly* mentioned or *implicitly required* to evaluate the claim.  \n2. **Examine the trajectory** (all previous thoughts, tool names, arguments, and observations) to see which of those entities you have already obtained a Wikipedia page for, and what information is still missing.  \n3. **Formulate `next_thought`** as a short, concrete sentence that (a) states what you have learned so far, (b) names the remaining entity or piece of evidence you still need, and (c) explains which tool you will use next and why.  \n4. **Select `next_tool_name`** from the allowed set: `search_wikipedia`, `lookup_wikipedia`, or `finish`.  \n   - Use **`search_wikipedia`** when you need to discover the exact article title for an entity you have not yet identified.  \n   - Use **`lookup_wikipedia`** when you already know the exact title and need the article text (or a specific fact) from it.  \n   - Use **`finish`** *only* when you have retrieved the full text of all three required Wikipedia pages (or you are certain no more relevant pages exist).  \n5. **Provide `next_tool_args`** as a **single‑line JSON object** matching the tool’s schema, e.g. `{"query": "…"} ` or `{"title": "…"} `. Do not include any extra whitespace or comments.  \n6. **Avoid unnecessary calls:** once a title is known and its page has been looked up, do not search for it again. Do not retrieve pages that are not directly needed to confirm the three entities.  \n7. **When calling `finish`**, leave `next_tool_args` empty (`{}`); the subsequent extraction module will read the trajectory and output the final list of titles.\n\n**Output format (exactly as shown, one field per line):**\n\n```\n\nBefore finish, ensure the three titles are distinct, directly relevant, and fully retrieved.\n\nYou are an Agent. In each episode, you will be given the field `claim` as input, and you can see your past `trajectory`.\nYour goal is to use the supplied tools to gather what you need.\n\nTools:\n(1) search_wikipedia: <desc>Returns top search results.</desc> Args: {"query": "string"}\n(2) lookup_wikipedia: <desc>Returns the text of a Wikipedia page.</desc> Args: {"title": "string"}\n(3) finish: <desc>Marks the task as complete.</desc> Args: {}\n\n\n### Example\nClaim: The father of Zak Ové and A. Edward Sutherland are not both photographers.\nTrajectory:\n[[ ## thought_0 ## ]]\nI need to locate Wikipedia pages for Zak Ové and his father, as well as for A. Edward Sutherland and his father, to determine whether each father was a photographer. I will start by searching for Zak Ové.\n\n[[ ## tool_name_0 ## ]]\nsearch_wikipedia\n\n[[ ## tool_args_0 ## ]]\n{"query": "Zak Ové"}\n\n[[ ## observation_0 ## ]]\n[1] «Zak Ové | Zak Ové (born 1966) is a British visual artist who works between sculpture, film and photography, living in London, UK, and Trinidad.  His themes reflect "his documentation of and anthropological interest in diasporic and African history, specifically that which is explored through Trinidadian carnival."  In work that is "filtered through his own personal and cultural upbringing, with a black Trinidadian father and white Irish mother", he has exhibited widely in Europe, the United States and Africa, participating in international museum shows in London, Dakar, Paris, Dubai, Prague, Berlin, Johannesburg, Bamako and New York City.  His father is the filmmaker Horace Ové and his sister is the actress Indra Ové.»\n[2] «Horace Ové | Horace Ové, CBE (born 1939), is a British filmmaker, photographer, painter and writer, one of the leading black independent film-makers to emerge in Britain since the post-war period.  Ové holds the "Guinness World Record" for being the first black British film-maker to direct a feature-length film, "Pressure" (1975).  In its retrospective history, "100 Years of Cinema", the British Film Institute (BFI) declared: "Horace Ové is undoubtedly a pioneer in Black British history and his work provides a perspective on the Black experience in Britain."»\n[3] «Indra Ové | Indra Ové (born 1968) is a British movie and stage actress.»\n[4] «Eugeniusz Zak | Eugeniusz Zak (15 December 1884 – 15 January 1926), also known as Eugène Zak and Eugene Zak, was a Polish artist.»\n[5] «Qorao‘zak District | Qorao‘zak District (Uzbek: "Qorao‘zak tumani" , Karakalpak: Qarao‘zek rayonı ) is a district of Karakalpakstan in Uzbekistan.  The capital lies at Qorao‘zak.»\n[6] «Other retrieved pages have titles: `Zak Zodiac`, `Qorao‘zak`, `Gershon Zak`, `Zak Smith`, `Zak the Baker`, `Frankie Zak`, `Zak Tales`, `Zak transform`, `John C. Zak`, `Playing Away`, `Zak\'s Lunch`, `Mendel Zaks`, `Zak Abel`, `Leocadia I. Zak`, `Zak Santiago`, `Zik Zak Filmworks`, `Zak Ibsen`, `Peter Zak`, `Zak Silver`, `Zak Ramsey`, `Zak Knutson`, `Zak Bucia`, `ZAK`, `Zak Boggs`, `Zak Boagey`.»\n\n[[ ## thought_1 ## ]]\nI need to find the Wikipedia page for A.\u202fEdward Sutherland to identify his father. Then I will look up the father\'s page (if it exists) to determine whether he was a photographer.\n\n[[ ## tool_name_1 ## ]]\nsearch_wikipedia\n\n[[ ## tool_args_1 ## ]]\n{"query": "A. Edward Sutherland"}\n\n[[ ## observation_1 ## ]]\n[1] «Henry Sutherland Edwards | Henry Sutherland Edwards (1828–1906) was a British journalist.»\n[2] «A. Edward Sutherland | Albert Edward Sutherland (January 5, 1895 – December 31, 1973) was a film director and actor.  Born in London, he was from a theatrical family.  His father, Al Sutherland, was a theatre manager and producer and his mother, Julie Ring, was a vaudeville performer.  He was a nephew of both Blanche Ring and Thomas Meighan, who was married to Frances Ring, another of his mother\'s sisters.»\n[3] «James Miller Sutherland | James Miller Sutherland (June 30, 1853 – 1921) was a lawyer and political figure in Prince Edward Island, Canada.  He represented 1st Queens in the Legislative Assembly of Prince Edward Island from 1887 to 1891 as a Liberal member.»\n[4] «Coming Through | Coming Through (1925) is a silent film directed by A. Edward Sutherland starring Thomas Meighan and Lila Lee.  The film was Sutherland\'s directorial debut and is now considered a lost film.»\n[5] «William Sutherland Maxwell | William Sutherland Maxwell (b. November 14, 1874 – March, 1952) was a well-known Canadian architect and a Hand of the Cause in the Bahá\'í Faith.  He was born in Montreal, Canada to parents Edward John Maxwell and Johan MacBean.»\n[6] «Other retrieved pages have titles: `We\'re in the Navy Now`, `David Edwards (judge)`, `It\'s the Old Army Game`, `Evelyn Edwards`, `Sing Your Worries Away`, `Mississippi (film)`, `Steel Against the Sky`, `Nine Lives Are Not Enough`, `Oxford University Exploration Club`, `Patrick Sutherland`, `Too Much Harmony`, `Fast Company (1929 film)`, `Love\'s Greatest Mistake`, `Secrets of the French Police`, `Wild, Wild Susan`, `Ivan Sutherland`, `Edward Goll`, `Mack &amp; Myer for Hire`, `Beyond Tomorrow (film)`, `William Sutherland, 17th Earl of Sutherland`, `Murders in the Zoo`, `What a Night! (1928 film)`, `The Lost Boys`, `Fireman, Save My Child (1927 film)`, `Warren G. Harding Supreme Court candidates`.»\n\n[[ ## thought_2 ## ]]\nI need to examine the Wikipedia page for Horace Ové to confirm whether he was a photographer. This will provide evidence about the father of Zak Ové.\n\n[[ ## tool_name_2 ## ]]\nlookup_wikipedia\n\n[[ ## tool_args_2 ## ]]\n{"title": "Horace Ové"}\n\n[[ ## observation_2 ## ]]\nHorace Ové, CBE (born 1939), is a British filmmaker, photographer, painter and writer, one of the leading black independent film-makers to emerge in Britain since the post-war period.  Ové holds the "Guinness World Record" for being the first black British film-maker to direct a feature-length film, "Pressure" (1975).  In its retrospective history, "100 Years of Cinema", the British Film Institute (BFI) declared: "Horace Ové is undoubtedly a pioneer in Black British history and his work provides a perspective on the Black experience in Britain."\n\n### Example\nClaim: The type of area Wiliwili are typically found in have a dominant tree species of Acacia koa. They are of the pea family.\nTrajectory:\n[[ ## thought_0 ## ]]\nThe claim mentions the plant “Wiliwili” and its typical habitat having a dominant tree species Acacia koa, and that Wiliwili belongs to the pea family. To verify this, I need Wikipedia pages for Wiliwili, Acacia koa, and the pea family (Fabaceae). I will start by searching for “Wiliwili” to get its article title.\n\n[[ ## tool_name_0 ## ]]\nsearch_wikipedia\n\n[[ ## tool_args_0 ## ]]\n{"query": "Wiliwili"}\n\n[[ ## observation_0 ## ]]\n[1] «Wiliwili | Wiliwili, with the scientific name Erythrina sandwicensis, is a species of flowering tree in the pea family, Fabaceae that is endemic to the Hawaiian Islands.  It is the only species of "Erythrina" that naturally occurs there.  It is typically found in Hawaiian tropical dry forests on leeward island slopes up to an elevation of 600 m .»\n[2] «Drought deciduous | Drought deciduous plants are those that drop their leaves during the dry season or periods of drought.  Examples include plants of the California coastal sage scrub community, and the leeward Hawaiian dry forest tree, the wiliwili ("Erythrina sandwicensis").  This may be contrasted to deciduous plants that drop their leaves during cold periods, or evergreen plants that have green leaves year-round.»\n[3] «Nothocestrum breviflorum | Nothocestrum breviflorum, commonly known as smallflower ʻ aiea, is a species of tree in the nightshade family, Solanaceae, that is endemic to the island of Hawaiʻ i.  It inhabits dry and mixed mesic forests at elevations of 180 - .  These forests are dominated by ʻ ōhiʻ a lehua ("Metrosideros polymorpha") and koa ("Acacia koa") or lama ("Diospyros sandwicensis"), while plants associated with smallflower ʻ aiea include wiliwili ("Erythrina sandwicensis") and uhiuhi ("Caesalpinia kavaiensis").  "N. breviflorum" reaches a height of 10 - .  It is threatened by habitat loss.  It is federally listed as an endangered species of the United States.  There are fewer than 50 individuals remaining.»\n[4] «Kokia drynarioides | Kokia drynarioides, commonly known as Hawaiian tree cotton, is a species of flowering plant in the mallow family, Malvaceae, that is endemic to the Big Island of Hawaii.  It inhabits dry forests at elevations of 455 - .  Associated plants include ʻ āheahea ("Chenopodium oahuense"), ʻ aʻ aliʻ i ("Dodonaea viscosa"), hala pepe ("Pleomele hawaiiensis"), wiliwili ("Erythrina sandwicensis"), uhiuhi ("Caesalpinia kavaiensis"), kōlea ("Myrsine lanaiensis"), ʻ aiea ("Nothocestrum latifolium"), kuluʻ ī ("Nototrichium sandwicense"), ʻ ālaʻ a ("Pouteria sandwicensis"), ʻ ohe kukuluāeʻ o ("Reynoldsia sandwicensis"), māmane ("Sophora chrysophylla"), and maua ("Xylosma hawaiiense" var.  "hillebrandii").  It is threatened by habitat loss and competition with invasive species, such as Fountain Grass ("Pennisetum setaceum").»\n[5] «Hawaiian tropical dry forests | The Hawaiian tropical dry forests are a tropical dry broadleaf forest ecoregion in the Hawaiian Islands.  They cover an area of 6600 km2 on the leeward side of the main islands and the summits of Niʻ ihau and Kahoʻ olawe.  These forests are either seasonal or sclerophyllous.  Annual rainfall is less than 127 cm and may be as low as 25 cm ; the rainy season lasts from November to March.  Dominant tree species include koa ("Acacia koa"), koaiʻ a ("A. koaia"), ʻ akoko ("Euphorbia" spp.) , ʻ ōhiʻ a lehua ("Metrosideros polymorpha"), lonomea ("Sapindus oahuensis"), māmane ("Sophora chrysophylla"), loulu ("Pritchardia" spp.) , lama ("Diospyros sandwicensis"), olopua ("Nestegis sandwicensis"), wiliwili ("Erythrina sandwicensis"), and ʻ iliahi ("Santalum" spp.) .  Endemic plant species in the dry forests include hau heleʻ ula ("Kokia cookei"), uhiuhi ("Caesalpinia kavaiensis"), and "Gouania" spp.  The palila ("Loxioides bailleui"), a Hawaiian honeycreeper, is restricted to this type of habitat.»\n[6] «Other retrieved pages have titles: ``, `Friends of the Parks`, `1984–85 European Cup Winners\' Cup`, `Presheaf (category theory)`, `Rock Me Gently (Erasure song)`, `Like a Rock (song)`, `Władysław Frasyniuk`, `Gulf, Mobile and Northern Railroad`, `Hida Minzoku Mura Folk Village`, `Texas State Highway 49`, `Delias belladonna`, `Secret Belgian binding`, `Sokolac`, `Fort Chaffee Maneuver Training Center`, `Love You till Tuesday (album)`, `Hampshire County Schools`, `Great Thessaloniki Fire of 1917`, `Leigh Delamere`, `Trabant (band)`, `Herman Teodor Holmgren`, `Molly Moo-Cow`, `List of fatal bear attacks in North America`, `Dirk Müller (racing driver)`, `25 Live`, `2004 World Snooker Championship`.»\n\n[[ ## thought_1 ## ]]\nI need the full Wikipedia article for Wiliwili to confirm its family (pea family) and typical habitat. I will look up the page titled “Wiliwili”.\n\n[[ ## tool_name_1 ## ]]\nlookup_wikipedia\n\n[[ ## tool_args_1 ## ]]\n{"title": "Wiliwili"}\n\n[[ ## observation_1 ## ]]\nWiliwili, with the scientific name Erythrina sandwicensis, is a species of flowering tree in the pea family, Fabaceae that is endemic to the Hawaiian Islands.  It is the only species of "Erythrina" that naturally occurs there.  It is typically found in Hawaiian tropical dry forests on leeward island slopes up to an elevation of 600 m .\n\n[[ ## thought_2 ## ]]\nTo verify the claim I need a source that describes the dominant tree species in the habitat where Wiliwili grows. The Wiliwili article says it is typically found in Hawaiian tropical dry forests. I will retrieve the Wikipedia page for “Hawaiian tropical dry forests” to see if Acacia koa is listed as a dominant species there. If needed I will also retrieve the Acacia koa page.\n\n[[ ## tool_name_2 ## ]]\nsearch_wikipedia\n\n[[ ## tool_args_2 ## ]]\n{"query": "Hawaiian tropical dry forests"}\n\n[[ ## observation_2 ## ]]\n[1] «Hawaiian tropical dry forests | The Hawaiian tropical dry forests are a tropical dry broadleaf forest ecoregion in the Hawaiian Islands.  They cover an area of 6600 km2 on the leeward side of the main islands and the summits of Niʻ ihau and Kahoʻ olawe.  These forests are either seasonal or sclerophyllous.  Annual rainfall is less than 127 cm and may be as low as 25 cm ; the rainy season lasts from November to March.  Dominant tree species include koa ("Acacia koa"), koaiʻ a ("A. koaia"), ʻ akoko ("Euphorbia" spp.) , ʻ ōhiʻ a lehua ("Metrosideros polymorpha"), lonomea ("Sapindus oahuensis"), māmane ("Sophora chrysophylla"), loulu ("Pritchardia" spp.) , lama ("Diospyros sandwicensis"), olopua ("Nestegis sandwicensis"), wiliwili ("Erythrina sandwicensis"), and ʻ iliahi ("Santalum" spp.) .  Endemic plant species in the dry forests include hau heleʻ ula ("Kokia cookei"), uhiuhi ("Caesalpinia kavaiensis"), and "Gouania" spp.  The palila ("Loxioides bailleui"), a Hawaiian honeycreeper, is restricted to this type of habitat.»\n[2] «Wiliwili | Wiliwili, with the scientific name Erythrina sandwicensis, is a species of flowering tree in the pea family, Fabaceae that is endemic to the Hawaiian Islands.  It is the only species of "Erythrina" that naturally occurs there.  It is typically found in Hawaiian tropical dry forests on leeward island slopes up to an elevation of 600 m .»\n[3] «Tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests | The tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forest biome, also known as tropical dry forest, monsoon forest, vine thicket, vine scrub and dry rainforest is located at tropical and subtropical latitudes.  Though these forests occur in climates that are warm year-round, and may receive several hundred centimeters of rain per year, they have long dry seasons which last several months and vary with geographic location.  These seasonal droughts have great impact on all living things in the forest.»\n[4] «Balsas dry forests | The Balsas dry forests are a tropical ecoregion, of the Tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests Biome, located in western and central Mexico.»\n[5] «Greater hedgehog tenrec | The greater hedgehog tenrec or large Madagascar hedgehog or sokina ("Setifer setosus", formerly known as Dasogale fontoynonti) is a species of mammal in the family Tenrecidae.  It is endemic to Madagascar.  Its natural habitats are subtropical or tropical dry forests, subtropical or tropical moist lowland forests, subtropical or tropical moist montane forests, dry savanna, moist savanna, subtropical or tropical dry shrubland, subtropical or tropical moist shrubland, subtropical or tropical high-altitude shrubland, subtropical or tropical dry lowland grassland, subtropical or tropical high-altitude grassland, rural gardens, urban areas and zoos.»\n[6] «Other retrieved pages have titles: `Zambezian cryptosepalum dry forest`, `Seasonal tropical forest`, `Tailless tenrec`, `Hottentot golden mole`, `Atlantic dry forests`, `Chiquitano dry forests`, `Hawaiian tropical rainforests`, `Mato Grosso tropical dry forests`, `Cauca Valley dry forests`, `Rufous-headed chachalaca`, `Cinnamon hummingbird`, `Southeastern Indochina dry evergreen forests`, `Cuban dry forests`, `Central Indochina dry forests`, `Bajío dry forests`, `Central American dry forests`, `Pacific parrotlet`, `Aeshna meruensis`, `Eritrea clawed frog`, `Highveld golden mole`, `Striped tree frog`, `Banded quail`, `Heterixalus boettgeri`, `Ballochia atro-virgata`, `Grey pileated finch`.»\n\n### Example\nClaim: 1990 Film that Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi is loosely based on stars this actor who is best known for martial arts action films.\nTrajectory:\n[[ ## thought_0 ## ]]\nI need to identify the 1990 film that "Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi" is loosely based on, and the actor who stars in that 1990 film and is best known for martial‑arts action movies. I will start by searching Wikipedia for information about "Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi" and its source material.\n\n[[ ## tool_name_0 ## ]]\nsearch_wikipedia\n\n[[ ## tool_args_0 ## ]]\n{"query": "Khiladiyon Ka Khidai loosely based on 1990 film"}\n\n[[ ## observation_0 ## ]]\n[1] «Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi | Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi (English: Player of Players) is a 1996 Indian action film starring Rekha in her first villain role, Akshay Kumar, Raveena Tandon and former WWE wrestlers "Crush" and Brian Lee as "The Undertaker".  It was the 5th highest grossing movie of the year 1996 and was declared \'SuperHit\' by Box Office India.  It was the fourth installment in the Khiladi (film series).  The movie is loosely based based on Hollywood film Lionheart»\n[2] «Inder Kumar | Inder Kumar (26 August 1973 – 28 July 2017) was an Indian actor best known for playing supporting roles in Hindi films such as "Wanted", "Tumko Na Bhool Paayenge", "Kahin Pyaar Na Ho Jaaye" and "Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi".»\n[3] «Luv Ka The End | Luv Ka The End ("The End of Luv") is a 2011 Hindi film directed by Bumpy, starring Shraddha Kapoor and Taaha Shah in the lead roles.  The film was the first production of Y-Films, a subsidiary of Yash Raj Films and released to mostly positive reviews on 6 May 2011.  The film is also loosely based on the 2009 American film "Wild Cherry" and "Paper Towns" novel by John Green.  It performed below average at the box office.»\n[4] «Umesh Mehra | Umesh Mehra is an Indian film director and producer of Bollywood.  He was prominent in the 1980s and 1990s with many Mithun Chakraborty starrers like "Ashanti" (1982), "Mujrim" (1989) and "Yaar Gaddar" (1994).  He directed Akshay Kumar in three films in the "Khiladi" series: "Sabse Bada Khiladi" (1995) "Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi" (1996) and "International Khiladi" (1999).  In 1998 he directed the veteran actor Dilip Kumar in "Qila" which was Kumar\'s last film to date.  Mehra\'s last film as director was 2002\'s "Yeh Mohabbat Hai".»\n[5] «Khiladi 420 | Khiladi 420 (English: "Con Player") is an Indian Hindi action film directed by Neeraj Vora and starring Akshay Kumar and Mahima Chaudhry.  The film was written by Uttam Gudda and released on 29 December 2000.  It is the seventh installment in the "Khiladi" series starring Kumar, which included "Khiladi" (1992), "Main Khiladi Tu Anari" (1994), "Sabse Bada Khiladi" (1995), "Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi" (1996), "Mr. and Mrs. Khiladi" (1997) and "International Khiladi" (1999).»\n[6] «Other retrieved pages have titles: `Watchers II`, `Khiladi (film series)`, `Gunahon Ka Devta (1990 film)`, `Aaj Ka Arjun`, `The Judas Project`, `Kamov Ka-40`, `Humanap Ka ng Panget`, `Pyaar Ka Saaya`, `The Amityville Curse`, `Doodh Ka Karz`, `Pyar Ka Karz`, `Gumapang Ka Sa Lusak`, `Then She Found Me`, `Pulan Visaranai`, `Aabra Ka Daabra`, `Loose Cannons (1990 film)`, `Khiladi (1992 film)`, `Kaalo`, `Taqdeer Ka Tamasha`, `The Nasty Girl`, `Tre colonne in cronaca`, `Muqaddar Ka Badshaah`, `Little White Dove`, `Working Girl (TV series)`, `Enteng Kabisote: Okay ka, Fairy Ko: The Legend`.»\n\n[[ ## thought_1 ## ]]\nThe search result indicates that *Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi* is loosely based on the 1990 Hollywood film **Lionheart**. To verify the starring actor—who is best known for martial‑arts action films—I will look up the Wikipedia page for that film.\n\n[[ ## tool_name_1 ## ]]\nlookup_wikipedia\n\n[[ ## tool_args_1 ## ]]\n{"title": "Lionheart (1990 film)"}\n\n[[ ## observation_1 ## ]]\nLionheart (also known as Wrong Bet, A.W.O.L.: Absent Without Leave, Leon and Full Contact) is a 1990 action film, directed by Sheldon Lettich, starring Jean-Claude Van Damme and co-starring Brian Thompson, along with Harrison Page, Deborah Rennard, Lisa Pelikan, and Ashley Johnson.\n\n[[ ## thought_2 ## ]]\nI need to confirm that the Wikipedia page for *Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi* states it is loosely based on the 1990 film *Lionheart*, and also verify that the starring actor of *Lionheart* (Jean‑Claude Van Damme) is described as being best known for martial‑arts action films. I will look up the page for *Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi*.\n\n[[ ## tool_name_2 ## ]]\nlookup_wikipedia\n\n[[ ## tool_args_2 ## ]]\n{"title": "Khiladiyon Ka Khiladi"}\n\n[[ ## observation_2 ## ]]\nKhiladiyon Ka Khiladi (English: Player of Players) is a 1996 Indian action film starring Rekha in her first villain role, Akshay Kumar, Raveena Tandon and former WWE wrestlers "Crush" and Brian Lee as "The Undertaker".  It was the 5th highest grossing movie of the year 1996 and was declared \'SuperHit\' by Box Office India.  It was the fourth installment in the Khiladi (film series).  The movie is loosely based based on Hollywood film Lionheart\n\n[[ ## thought_3 ## ]]\nTo verify the claim I must confirm that the actor starring in the 1990 film *Lionheart* (Jean‑Claude Van Damme) is described on Wikipedia as being best known for martial‑arts action films. I will look up the Wikipedia page for Jean‑Claude Van Damme.\n\n[[ ## tool_name_3 ## ]]\nlookup_wikipedia\n\n[[ ## tool_args_3 ## ]]\n{"title": "Jean-Claude Van Damme"}\n\n[[ ## observation_3 ## ]]\nJean-Claude Camille François Van Varenberg (born 18 October 1960), professionally known as Jean-Claude Van Damme and abbreviated as JCVD, is a Belgian actor, martial artist, screenwriter, film producer, and director best known for his martial arts action films.  The most successful of these films include "Bloodsport" (1988), "Kickboxer" (1989), "Lionheart" (1990), "Double Impact" (1991), "Universal Soldier" (1992), "Hard Target" (1993), "Street Fighter" (1994), "Timecop" (1994), "Sudden Death" (1995), "JCVD" (2008) and "The Expendables 2" (2012).\n\nClaim: The coach alongside  will.i.am and Pixie Lott on The Voice Kids (UK TV series), and Aleksi Sihvonen, are both vocalist.\n\nTrajectory:\n\n\n**OUTPUT RULES:**\n- Do NOT use <think>...</think> tags - output JSON directly!\n- Return EXACTLY a JSON object with these keys:\n  - "next_thought": string (your reasoning for this step)\n  - "next_tool_name": one of ["search_wikipedia","lookup_wikipedia","finish"]\n  - "next_tool_args": JSON object matching the chosen tool schema\n\nOutput (JSON only):'}], 'image_urls': []}, response={'token_ids': [], 'raw_content': None}, reward=-0.041, metadata={'request': {'type': 'chat', 'model': 'Qwen/Qwen3-8B', 'max_tokens': 1024, 'temperature': 0.0, 'streaming': False}, 'response': None, 'response_id': None, 'agent_name': '*'}), Triplet(prompt={'token_ids': [], 'raw_content': [{'role': 'user', 'content': 'Find all Wikipedia titles relevant to verifying (or refuting) the claim.\n\nGiven the claim and the full trajectory (tool calls + observations), output the final list of Wikipedia article titles that should be returned.\n\n**CRITICAL OUTPUT RULES:**\n- Output EXACTLY one JSON object: {"titles": ["Title1", "Title2", "..."]}\n- Do NOT use <think>...</think> tags - output JSON directly!\n- Do NOT include explanations, reasoning, or any other text.\n- Your response must start with \'{\' and end with \'}\'.\n- Titles must be strings (Wikipedia article titles), no duplicates.\n\nClaim: The coach alongside  will.i.am and Pixie Lott on The Voice Kids (UK TV series), and Aleksi Sihvonen, are both vocalist.\n\nTrajectory:\n[[ ## thought_0 ## ]]\nRITS call failed: Authentication failed\n\n[[ ## tool_name_0 ## ]]\nfinish\n\n[[ ## tool_args_0 ## ]]\n{}\n\n[[ ## observation_0 ## ]]\nCompleted.\n\n\nOutput (JSON only):'}], 'image_urls': []}, response={'token_ids': [], 'raw_content': None}, reward=-0.041, metadata={'reques